{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517918"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:58:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:58:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.7,0.08,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5288"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77300"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5288"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62807"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"5841"},{"type":"tags","id":"6255"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77300"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the rheumatology clinic with a one-year history of right knee and widespread finger joint pain. The pain is intermittent, but has been getting worse and is particularly worse after exercise. These joints feel stiff first thing in the morning for around 10 minutes and he is now taking paracetamol regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is restricted movement in the affected joints, palpable crepitus in the affected knee joint, Heberden\u0027s nodes and swelling of his fingers, with mild muscle wasting of the quadriceps muscle. His BMI is 33.5 kg/m^2. His laboratory investigation results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EESR: 11.5mm/hr (0-30).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 2.3mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 145g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocytes: 6.7 x 10^9 cells/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome X-rays are to be arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following radiological findings is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Periarticular osteopaenia","Osteophytosis","Pencil-in-cup deformity","Joint space widening","Ivory phalanx"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with what is almost certainly osteoarthritis (OA) because of the history of pain exacerbated by movement, brief morning stiffness and the presence of examination findings consistent with osteoarthritis (Heberden\u0027s nodes, decreased range of joint movement and joint crepitus). The normal laboratory investigations support a diagnosis of OA. The patient also has risk factors for the development of OA including advanced age and obesity. \u003Cstrong\u003EOsteophytosis \u003C/strong\u003E(i.e., osteophyte development) is one of the most common radiological findings found in patients with OA. These are cartilage-capped bony proliferations (bony spurs) that most commonly develop at the margins of a synovial joint as a response to articular cartilage damage. The examination finding of Heberden\u0027s nodes is also because of the formation of osteophytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriarticular osteopaenia \u003C/strong\u003Eis usually found in patients with rheumatoid arthritis, which would have presented with pain exacerbating on rest and morning stiffness of more than 15 minutes. ESR and CRP are also found to be raised in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epencil-in-cup deformity \u003C/strong\u003Eresults from periarticular erosions and bone resorption giving the appearance of a pencil in a cup. It is an uncommon finding associated with psoriatic arthritis. and found in less than 5% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint space widening\u003C/strong\u003E can be found in a number of disease processes and is most often due to a joint effusion. This can be a result of septic arthritis, inflammatory arthritis, trauma or rarely, malignancy. There are no features of the patient\u0027s clinical evaluation or laboratory investigations to suggest any of these differentials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIvory phalanx \u003C/strong\u003Eis a radiological finding that is found in patients with psoriatic arthritis and consists of increased radiodensity of an entire phalanx as a result of periosteal and endosteal bone formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteophyte formation is a characteristic feature of osteoarthritis."],"references":["Chalian M, Roemer FW, Guermazi A. Advances in osteoarthritis imaging. Curr Opin Rheumatol. 2023 Jan 1;35(1):44-54. doi: 10.1097/BOR.0000000000000917. Epub 2022 Nov 11. PMID: 36377320.","Roemer FW, Crema MD, Trattnig S, Guermazi A. Advances in imaging of osteoarthritis and cartilage. Radiology. 2011 Aug;260(2):332-54. doi: 10.1148/radiol.11101359. PMID: 21778451.","Junker S, Krumbholz G, Frommer KW, Rehart S, Steinmeyer J, Rickert M, Schett G, M\u00fcller-Ladner U, Neumann E. Differentiation of osteophyte types in osteoarthritis - proposal of a histological classification. Joint Bone Spine. 2016 Jan;83(1):63-7. doi: 10.1016/j.jbspin.2015.04.008. Epub 2015 Jun 12. PMID: 26076655."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62807"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62807"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:41:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:41:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5288"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77300"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemC